Secure networks: Thread networks feature secure, banking-class encryption. Thread closes identified security holes found in other wireless protocols and provides worry-free operation.
Simple connectivity: Thread devices are simple to install with a smartphone, tablet or computer. Consumers can securely connect Thread devices in the home to each other and to the cloud for easy control and access from anywhere.
Low power: Thread supports battery-operated devices as part of a home network. This allows the devices that people use every day - including thermostats, lighting controls, safety and security products - to be a part of the network without requiring constant charging or frequent battery changes.

Millions of existing 802.15.4 wireless devices already on the market can run Thread with just a software enhancement -- no new hardware required. Thread is designed for quick implementation and deployment of devices throughout the home.
Close Answer




Is Thread available now?


Thread is available to members as of July 13th 2015. 
Close Answer





How will I know if a connected home product is Thread certified?


Look for products bearing the “Built on Thread” logo. These devices have undergone and passed rigorous Thread network testing and certification.
Close Answer




How does Thread increase customer satisfaction?


Thread provides a new and better way to connect and control products in the home. Consumers can simply and securely add and remove products to the network via a smartphone, table or computer. All Thread-certified products are rigorously tested to ensure that they work together effortlessly and securely at the networking layer. This means that “Built on Thread” devices can talk to each other. The actual communication and user experience is defined by the application.
Close Answer



Open Thread

What is OpenThread? 


OpenThread is an open-source implementation of the Thread networking protocol technology, developed and released by Nest, and maintained on GitHub.
Close Answer




What is the difference between Thread and OpenThread?


OpenThread is an open source implementation of Thread technology, based on the draft Thread 1.0 specification, which was released by Nest. Developers who chose to use OpenThread in shipping products must join the Thread Group in order to certify those products and market them as Thread-certified.
Close Answer




Is an end-product based on OpenThread automatically Thread-certified? 


No. If a company uses OpenThread to build an end-product, they will need to be a member of the Thread Group in order to gain the Intellectual Property (IP) rights to ship Thread products, and to complete product certification, which ensures that products using Thread will work together effortlessly and securely right out of the box. 
Close Answer




What would prevent a company from shipping a product based on OpenThread without joining the Thread Group?


If developers choose not to join Thread Group and ship products using Thread technology, they are not conferred the IP rights required to practice and ship Thread technology, and may subject themselves to legal action, including but not limited to licensing fees.
Close Answer




Was the Thread Group involved in Nest's creation of OpenThread?


No. The Thread specification is available to all members of the Thread Group. Nest added Thread technology to GitHub to make it available to more developers. For any OpenThread products to be Thread-certified or marketed as such, the company would still need to join the Thread Group and complete the product certification program.
Close Answer













 








